1
00:00:00,001 --> 00:00:03,001
In this lesson, we will talk about testing your content for accessibility.

2
00:00:04,860 --> 00:00:07,860
If you watched the first lesson on this topic, you're already familiar with the term accessibility

3
00:00:09,700 --> 00:00:12,700
and aware of its importance.

4
00:00:11,760 --> 00:00:14,760
Let's recap.

5
00:00:13,560 --> 00:00:16,560
Digital accessibility is a broad term that ensures that as many people as possible can

6
00:00:17,780 --> 00:00:20,780
use the web, be it operating an online service or consuming online content.

7
00:00:23,280 --> 00:00:26,280
While accessibility has legal and business implications, it's important to remember

8
00:00:27,440 --> 00:00:30,440
that these guidelines promise a better browsing experience for everyone.

9
00:00:32,200 --> 00:00:35,200
The easiest way to guarantee that your site is accessible is to consider doing the design

10
00:00:36,680 --> 00:00:39,680
and development.

11
00:00:37,680 --> 00:00:40,680
However, block-based themes offer incredible flexibility and with great power comes great

12
00:00:43,480 --> 00:00:46,480
responsibility.

13
00:00:45,280 --> 00:00:48,280
Fortunately, many technical accessibility problems are usually easy to detect and fix

14
00:00:50,200 --> 00:00:53,200
using automated tools.

15
00:00:52,400 --> 00:00:55,400
Proper heading levels, color contrast, meaningful alt text, link text and so on.

16
00:00:57,680 --> 00:01:00,680
Ironically, these are the most common accessibility fails on the web.

17
00:01:02,400 --> 00:01:05,400
In this tutorial, we'll focus on reversing the strand and show you how to test the content

18
00:01:07,400 --> 00:01:10,400
you create before publishing and ensure your posts and pages are usable.

19
00:01:12,280 --> 00:01:15,280
WordPress includes two built-in accessibility helpers in the Editor.

20
00:01:16,880 --> 00:01:19,880
Number 1 - Semantic Structure. Click on Document Overview and then Outline

21
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:25,000
to check whether your headings are ordered correctly.

22
00:01:24,800 --> 00:01:27,800
Starting from H2 and continuing in a descending sequence up to H6 without skipping over.

23
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:34,600
WordPress marks the wrong heading levels in light orange and notifies you if you are

24
00:01:35,680 --> 00:01:38,680
using an incorrect heading level.

25
00:01:38,920 --> 00:01:41,920
Number 2 - Color Contrast. If you select a text and background color

26
00:01:43,040 --> 00:01:46,040
combination that fails to provide sufficient contrast, WordPress will alert you indicating

27
00:01:48,520 --> 00:01:51,520
that this color combination may be hard for people to read.

28
00:01:51,960 --> 00:01:54,960
Try using contrasting colors for the background and text to enhance accessibility.

29
00:01:57,120 --> 00:02:00,120
Fix these and you're already better than most of the big sites on the internet.

30
00:02:01,760 --> 00:02:04,760
To fix the color contrast, select the relevant block, in this case the Buttons block, and

31
00:02:07,760 --> 00:02:10,760
then open up Styles in your sidebar settings on the right.

32
00:02:11,440 --> 00:02:14,440
And then below color we can change the background color and then the text color to ensure the

33
00:02:18,400 --> 00:02:21,400
colors contrast well.

34
00:02:20,760 --> 00:02:23,760
Next, let's explore a few accessibility plugins.

35
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:28,000
WP Tota11y, Sa11y and Editoria11y are variations of each other.

36
00:02:30,080 --> 00:02:33,080
WordPress Tota11y is a lightweight plugin that checks common accessibility compliance

37
00:02:34,320 --> 00:02:37,320
both on the front end and the Editor, notifying you of any incorrect heading levels, color

38
00:02:40,640 --> 00:02:43,640
contrast, poor link text, missing labels in form elements, and missing alt text in images.

39
00:02:47,960 --> 00:02:50,960
The tool has a neat experimental feature called Screen Reader Wand to view elements

40
00:02:52,840 --> 00:02:55,840
as a screen reader would.

41
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:57,800
You can navigate through the alerts in each category and review the suggested fix, but

42
00:03:00,120 --> 00:03:03,120
it's suggested to do it in the front end as it can be confusing in the Editor as it checks

43
00:03:04,720 --> 00:03:07,720
the entire browser window.

44
00:03:06,920 --> 00:03:09,920
Number 2 - Sa11y Sally provides a comprehensive

45
00:03:10,280 --> 00:03:13,280
set of checks on the front end.

46
00:03:12,440 --> 00:03:15,440
You can toggle a few extra checks such as readability, advanced links, color contrast

47
00:03:17,560 --> 00:03:20,560
and form labels under Settings, where you'll also find color filters to test how your page

48
00:03:23,640 --> 00:03:26,640
would look when viewed by people with several types of colorblindness.

49
00:03:27,960 --> 00:03:30,960
While the errors are clearly marked, the description is more high level and the fix isn't as

50
00:03:32,360 --> 00:03:35,360
straightforward as it could be.

51
00:03:34,840 --> 00:03:37,840
Sa11y enables Administrators to define and control various functions on its advanced

52
00:03:39,640 --> 00:03:42,640
setting admin page.

53
00:03:42,720 --> 00:03:45,720
Editora11y focuses on content and structure.

54
00:03:45,880 --> 00:03:48,880
No design elements like color contrast will be checked.

55
00:03:49,360 --> 00:03:52,360
When enabled, it displays alerts on the front end and the Editor notifying you about the

56
00:03:54,600 --> 00:03:57,600
document outline, heading levels, link texts and targets, also known as Open in a new tab

57
00:04:00,880 --> 00:04:03,880
and missing alt text in images.

58
00:04:03,680 --> 00:04:06,680
Its goal is to help writers and editors catch common problems and it describes the failures

59
00:04:08,480 --> 00:04:11,480
in plain language, suggests fixes and allows users to hide or dismiss the alert when it's

60
00:04:14,640 --> 00:04:17,640
irrelevant.

61
00:04:16,640 --> 00:04:19,640
Editora11y also generates reports and enables administrators to exclude alerts, skip some

62
00:04:21,920 --> 00:04:24,920
tests or include elements based on CSS selectors.

63
00:04:25,840 --> 00:04:28,840
Alternatively, there's the popular Accessibility Checker that adds a new section to the post

64
00:04:31,080 --> 00:04:34,080
or page editor window and a hovering button to the front end.

65
00:04:35,120 --> 00:04:38,120
It displays a summary of the errors, detailed explanations including the relevant code snippet,

66
00:04:40,600 --> 00:04:43,600
potential fixes and an option to ignore individual alerts.

67
00:04:45,960 --> 00:04:48,960
If you want to go the extra mile and test additional technical aspects, you can do the

68
00:04:50,280 --> 00:04:53,280
following.

69
00:04:51,280 --> 00:04:54,280
Number one, try browsing your website with a keyboard.

70
00:04:55,280 --> 00:04:58,280
No mouse.

71
00:04:56,480 --> 00:04:59,480
Use the tab key to navigate between links, buttons and form fields and press enter or

72
00:05:01,600 --> 00:05:04,600
space to activate these interactive elements of the page.

73
00:05:06,040 --> 00:05:09,040
Make note of non-functional elements and missing visual indicators that need fixing.

74
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:14,000
And secondly, you can change the device's color scheme to ensure things look and work

75
00:05:15,360 --> 00:05:18,360
well in dark or high contrast mode.

76
00:05:18,760 --> 00:05:21,760
To conclude, as you can see authors and content managers who create or maintain the content

77
00:05:23,680 --> 00:05:26,680
have direct control over critical aspects like heading levels, text size, color contrast,

78
00:05:30,240 --> 00:05:33,240
links, alternative text for images and more.

79
00:05:33,760 --> 00:05:36,760
In other words, you can avoid producing inaccessible content without touching the code.

80
00:05:39,720 --> 00:05:42,720
Just be mindful and empathetic.

